<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFC0F5C9ECE075981" box="[948,1044,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and it could be hard to distinguish these three species. In all of these species, abdominal segment 7 is black with posterior 1/2 or posterior 1/3 orange; in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFF0E5CD6CB0659C9" box="[181,277,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFF0E5CD6CB0659C9" box="[181,277,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is typically 1/2 orange but the degree of coloration can vary. 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFC5C5CD6CED759C9" baseAuthorityName="Bernhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[999,1220,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFC5C5CD6CED759C9" box="[999,1220,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Xanthopygus major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFB475CD6CF5859C9" box="[1276,1355,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="max">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFB475CD6CF5859C9" box="[1276,1355,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. max</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFEC95D0ACBC1582D" box="[370,466,259,284]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFEC95D0ACBC1582D" box="[370,466,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the following characteristics in combination: head and pronotum with small to medium size (see 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D38F87EFEC15D2EC8135870" box="[378,512,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–26" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[214,1366,665,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-148@12.[214,1373,658,1932]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 23–26. Xanthopygus major (Bernhauer). 23. Habitus photograph. 24. Pronotum. 25. Sternites 6–8. 26. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048501/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Figs. 23–24</figureCitation>
) punctures (medium to large size punctures in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFBBC5D2ECE765871" box="[1031,1125,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFBBC5D2ECE765871" box="[1031,1125,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); pronotum with one sparse row of punctures on each half beside median line (pronotum with 1–2 dense rows of punctures on each half beside median line in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFE845D66CB8C58B9" box="[319,415,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFE845D66CB8C58B9" box="[319,415,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); abdominal segments 4–6 not iridescent under strong light (abdominal segments 4–6 with iridescent overtones under strong light in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFDCA5D9AC8C2589D" box="[625,721,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pexus">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFDCA5D9AC8C2589D" box="[625,721,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. pexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFD525D9AC9D4589D" baseAuthorityName="Bernhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[745,967,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFD525D9AC9D4589D" box="[745,967,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Xanthopygus major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be confidently distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFA3F5D9ACAD558E1" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="max">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFA3F5D9ACAD558E1" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. max</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only by examining the paramere; in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFDDB5DBEC8D158E1" baseAuthorityName="Bernhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[608,706,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFDDB5DBEC86258E1" box="[608,625,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFDC45DBEC8D158E1" box="[639,706,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the paramere is apically rounded, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="2BA1668C4D38F87EFB7B5DBECF1D58E1" box="[1216,1294,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="max">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFB7B5DBECF1D58E1" box="[1216,1294,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">X. max</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is apically emarginate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A4BB4E844D38F87EFF7C5DF7CEF95A94" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" type="description">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D38F87EFF7C5DF7CEF95A94" blockId="13.[151,1437,150,1041]" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D38F87EFF7C5DF7CB4A5B29" bold="true" box="[199,345,510,536]" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Description.</emphasis>
Forebody length 
<quantity id="2B59B0EA4D38F87EFD9F5DF7C8D05B28" box="[548,707,510,537]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.205" metricValueMax="1.26" metricValueMin="1.15" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" unit="mm" value="12.05" valueMax="12.6" valueMin="11.5">11.5–12.6mm</quantity>
; HW/HL ratio = 1.27. Antennomere 3 longer to 2; antennomere 4 subquadrate, with tomentose pubescence; antennomere 6 transverse. Mandibles curved from apical half. Eyes as long as 1/3 length of head; head appearing convex. Head and pronotum with small to medium size punctures (see 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D38F87EFF2C5E62CB325BB4" box="[151,289,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–26" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[214,1366,665,1930]" captionTargetId="figure-148@12.[214,1373,658,1932]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 23–26. Xanthopygus major (Bernhauer). 23. Habitus photograph. 24. Pronotum. 25. Sternites 6–8. 26. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048501/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Figs. 23–24</figureCitation>
); pronotum with one sparse row of punctures on each half beside median line; pronotum microsculpture with transverse lines. PW/PL ratio = 1.10. Mesoventrite with intercoxal process broad and rounded. Metacoxae with more than four spines (five or six) on posterior surface. EL/PL ratio = 1.28. Abdominal segments 4–6 without iridescent overtones; segment 6 without distinct bright band of orange coloration posteriorly; tergite 6 densely punctate; sternite 6 with single anterior transverse line; segment 7 black with posterior 1/4 orange. In males, sternite 7 without porose structure; sternite 8 with shallow U-shaped emargination posteriorly. Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D38F87EFB4E5F16CF6F5A08" box="[1269,1404,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–29" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1849,1873]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,1065,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-422@13.[151,1436,1065,1826]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 27–29. Aedeagus of X. major (Bernhauer). 27. Dorsal view. 28. Lateral view. 29. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048503" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048503/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Figs. 27–29</figureCitation>
; in dorsal view paramere converging to rounded apex; paramere shorter and narrower than median lobe; in lateral view paramere almost straight; paramere with peg setae as in 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D38F87EFCB15F6EC94E5AB0" box="[778,861,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–29" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1849,1873]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,1065,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-422@13.[151,1436,1065,1826]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 27–29. Aedeagus of X. major (Bernhauer). 27. Dorsal view. 28. Lateral view. 29. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048503" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048503/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="164">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
. Median lobe in dorsal view converging to rounded apex; median lobe with subapical tooth; in lateral view median lobe becoming narrower near apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A4BB4E844D38F87EFF7C5FA7CBB45D20" pageId="13" pageNumber="164" type="distribution">
